TETRODOTOXIN, SEA SLUG, CANINE - NEW ZEALAND
********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Fri 14 Aug 2009
Source: Auckland Regional Council [edited]
<http://www.arc.govt.nz/council/news-and-events/regionwide-news/>


Dead dog contains same toxin as sea slug sample
-----------------------------------------------
Tests done by the Cawthron Institute have confirmed that the toxin
found in the vomit of one of the dogs that died after visiting Narrow
Neck Beach was also found in a sea slug sample taken from that beach.

The toxin has been identified as tetrodotoxin, which is also found in
tropical puffer fish. How the sea slugs came to contain the toxin is
not known and investigations are continuing.

Monitoring of Auckland's east coast and Coromandel beaches yesterday
[13 Aug 2009] found evidence of dead sea slugs only at Narrow Neck
and Cheltenham beaches. This tends to suggest that the issue could be
localised.

Auckland Regional Council (ARC) will continue to monitor Auckland
beaches for sea slugs and will conduct tests on any samples for the toxin.

Reported deaths of pilchards, penguins and dolphins are still being
investigated.

The Hauraki Gulf is a national icon and marine park. ARC Chairman
Mike Lee reminded Aucklanders today [14 Aug 2009] that we must all be
constantly vigilant to maintain the health and vitality of this treasure.

