[While the 2nd article is more research related, and was published on
7 Aug 2009, it has been included to provide other researchers method
of seeing what is done at the Cawthron Institute and foster some collaboration.

The 1st article is the most recent and has identified the toxin as
tetrodotoxin. This is generally associated with puffer fish.

How the toxin arrived in the sea slugs is quite mysterious. Dogs on
the other hand will consume the sea slugs on the shore (that's a
tongue twister) and acquire the same toxin.

Tetrodotoxin, a very potent toxin, selectively blocks the
voltage-sensitive sodium channels of excitable tissues and neuronal
transmission in skeletal muscles. In humans, paresthesias begin 10-45
minutes after ingestion, usually as tingling of the tongue and inner
surface of the mouth. Other common symptoms include vomiting,
lightheadedness, dizziness, feelings of doom, and weakness. Paralysis
spreads, and death can occur within 6-24 hours, often due to
paralysis of the muscles of respiration. Other signs include
salivation, muscle twitching, diaphoresis, pleuritic chest pain,
dysphagia, aphonia, and convulsions. Severe poisoning is indicated by
hypotension, bradycardia, depressed corneal reflexes, and fixed
dilated pupils. There is no specific antidote and treatment is often
supportive.

It is likely that dogs react to tetrodotoxin in approximately the
same mechanism as humans do. Consequently, they are not likely to
have an easy death.

There are a number of different species of puffer fish or blow fish,
each of which produces a different concentration of the toxin. - Mod.TG]

[The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of New Zealand is
available at <http://healthmap.org/r/00Ht>. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]
